<DOCNO> LA062389-0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 73613 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 23, 1989, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 7; Column 1; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
408 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMENTARY / EXCERPTS; 
</P>
<P>
GRAND FLAG, GREAT LIBERTIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EDWIN M. YODER JR. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Supreme Court now says that as long as there is a message in the act, 
flag-burning is not vandalism but a protected form of "symbolic" speech. At the 
simplest level, the logic is elementary. It is obvious that "symbolic speech" 
will involve the use, and even the occasional abuse, of symbols. 
</P>
<P>
And it is offensive free speech that usually needs judicial protection: The 
power to communicate sometimes involves the power to shock. 
</P>
<P>
None of these ideas are especially new, though they are more familiar in the 
field of artistic modernism than in constitutional law. Verbal and plastic art 
in our century has often explored outer limits of sensation. The language of 
some poetry, the grotesqueness (as it seems to conventional eyes) of some 
abstract art -- these are examples of what courts have often protected, even 
though the most provocative forms of expression have offended millions. 
</P>
<P>
It was inevitable that symbolism as a technique of "speech" would seep into 
First Amendment law; that "symbolic speech," though very possibly undreamed of 
by the framers of the First Amendment, would raid the armory of art to enhance 
and expand its powers to provoke. 
</P>
<P>
The difficulty is in drawing the lines. Some carry symbolic free speech to all 
imaginable lengths. Others, provoked by the court's previous tolerance of 
pornography or topless dancing, would reject the very idea that free speech 
should permit anything other than the most literal and straightforward 
"political" expression. 
</P>
<P>
Historically, they have a point. Before perceptions were turned upside down by 
modernists like Yeats and Joyce and Eliot, Picasso and Braque, it was as hard 
to imagine such issues as it was to imagine, before the invention of flying 
machines, how the Commerce Clause might apply to aviation. 
</P>
<P>
The court strongly intimates that it is not licensing casual or gratuitous 
vandalism against the flag -- that without a distinct "expressive" purpose, 
flag-burning will continue to be a crime. But even with all the hedging, 
successor controversies can be imagined springing from the fertile minds of 
First Amendment lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
Is it "symbolic speech," for instance, to spray-paint a swastika on a 
synagogue, or burn a cross in someone's front yard? Most of us would scoff at 
the mere idea that such outrages might follow logically from the toleration of 
flag-burning. But where are the "bright lines" (as judges like to say) that 
distinguish the one from the other? 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
