<TEXT>
<P>
An abandoned Salinas hotel that once counted author John Steinbeck and many 
U.S. Presidents among its guests has been temporarily saved from the wrecker's 
ball. Monterey County Superior Court Judge John M. Phillips found that the city 
had failed to get an adequate environmental impact report before ordering the 
Cominos Hotel demolished. The downtown hotel, built in 1874 and modernized in 
1919, was often visited and mentioned by Steinbeck, a Salinas native whose 
fiction won the Nobel Prize for literature. The hotel recently fell on hard 
times and the City Council voted in April to raze it for a parking lot, an 
office building and a museum dedicated to Steinbeck. The Monterey County 
Historical Society sued to save the hotel, arguing that the city's 
environmental document was deficient. 
</P>
